 succeeded in 0ms:
   761	with a subprocess pytest invocation per codex review round 0 finding 5.
   762	The meta scenario:
   763	
   764	1. **Constructs a `MisbehavingAdapter`** that wraps `ReferenceAdapter`
   765	   with an in-process httpx-Mocked-Transport-shaped HTTP proxy
   766	   (see below). The proxy:
   767	   - Listens on its own ephemeral port.
   768	   - Forwards all requests transparently to the underlying real IUT.
   769	   - Special-cases ONE URL pattern (`POST /v0/.../tasks/.../submit`
   770	     with a token mismatch detected by reading and re-emitting the
   771	     real backend's response): if the real IUT would have returned
   772	     403 `eden://error/wrong-token`, the proxy mutates the response
   773	     to 200 OK with a fabricated success body.
   774	   - Maintains a `mutation_count` counter incremented whenever it
   775	     mutated a response.
   776	   - Lifecycle is context-managed: enter → start proxy → real IUT;
   777	     exit → real IUT.stop() → proxy.stop().
   778	
   779	2. **Runs three subprocess pytest invocations** via
   780	   `subprocess.run([sys.executable, "-m", "pytest", ...])`:
   781	
   782	   a. **Control run (must pass).** Target:
   783	      `conformance/scenarios/test_claim_tokens.py::test_wrong_token_rejected`
   784	      against the unmodified `ReferenceAdapter`.
   785	      Assertion: exit code 0.
   786	
   787	   b. **Broken run (must fail).** Same target test against
   788	      `MisbehavingAdapter`. Assertion: exit code != 0 AND
   789	      `--json-report-file` shows `test_wrong_token_rejected` as
   790	      `outcome=failed` AND its `longrepr` contains the substring
   791	      `"Expected 403 wrong-token, got 200"` (the exact assertion
   792	      text from the broken scenario; this proves the failure was the
   793	      expected assertion, not an import error or proxy-startup
   794	      error).
   795	
   796	   c. **Hit counter check (must be ≥ 1).** After the broken run,
   797	      read the `MisbehavingAdapter`'s `mutation_count` (exposed via
   798	      a sidecar file the proxy writes to; the meta test reads it
   799	      after the subprocess exits). Assertion: count ≥ 1.
   800	
   801	3. **All three assertions pass** ⇒ the meta scenario is the proof
   802	   that the suite has teeth. Any single-failure fails the meta.
   803	
   804	The proxy implementation lives at
   805	[`conformance/scenarios/_meta/_misbehave_proxy.py`](../../conformance/scenarios/_meta/_misbehave_proxy.py)
   806	and uses `aiohttp` (pinned in `conformance/pyproject.toml`). It is
   807	~80 lines: a single-purpose forwarder that mutates one specific
   808	response shape. It is **not** a general MITM library.
   809	
   810	The misbehaving adapter exposes its own `--shared-token` because the
   811	sidecar misbehaving proxy needs to read+forward authenticated requests
   812	unchanged.
   813	
   814	#### F.1 Why three sub-runs
   815	
   816	- The control run (a) defends against false-positives: if a real bug
   817	  has already broken the wrong-token assertion in the suite, the
   818	  control fails and we know the meta scenario isn't the right
   819	  diagnosis.
   820	- The broken run (b) defends against silent harness regressions: if
   821	  someone refactors the wrong-token check away, the broken run starts
   822	  passing, and the meta fires.
   823	- The hit counter (c) defends against drift in the proxy itself: if
   824	  the harness changes how it tests wrong-token (e.g., starts using a
   825	  different URL or status code), the proxy stops matching the request,
   826	  the broken run still fails (because `wrong-token` no longer fires),
   827	  but the hit counter goes to 0 and the meta fires.
   828	
   829	#### F.2 Why this is not "just an extra test"
   830	
   831	The self-validation scenario is the closest thing to a proof that the
   832	suite asserts what it claims. Chapter 09 §3 leans on this scenario
   833	when it says "every assertion in the suite is keyed off a normative
   834	MUST." The meta is the integrity check that connects the assertion
   835	text to a concrete observable failure.
   836	
   837	### G. Spec chapter 09
   838	
   839	Chapter 09 is short by design. The chapter's job is to declare the
   840	relationship between the spec, the suite, and any IUT — not to
   841	duplicate content from chapters 02 / 04 / 05 / 06 / 07 / 08.
   842	
   843	```markdown
   844	# Conformance
   845	
   846	This chapter declares what conformance to EDEN protocol v0 means and
   847	how it is verified.
   848	
   849	## 1. What conformance is
   850	
   851	A v0-conforming IUT (implementation under test) implements chapter
   852	07's HTTP wire binding with the normative semantics of chapters 02 /
   853	03 / 04 / 05 / 06 / 08.
   854	
   855	Conformance is verified by passing the conformance suite under
   856	[`conformance/`](../../conformance/) in this repo: a set of black-box
   857	scenarios that drive an IUT through chapter-07 HTTP and assert MUSTs
   858	from those chapters. The suite is delivered in three increments —
   859	**v1**, **v1+roles**, and **v1+roles+integrator** — each adding a
   860	group of scenarios to the prior level. An IUT MAY claim the level
   861	that matches the scenarios it passes; "v0 conformance" without a
   862	qualifier means the highest level shipped at the time of the claim.
   863	
   864	The suite is one expression, not the only one. A future suite — in a
   865	different language, against a different harness — that drives the same
   866	chapter-07 endpoints and asserts the same MUSTs would be equally
   867	authoritative. The spec is the source of truth; the suite is one
   868	faithful implementation of "what would test that?"
   869	
   870	## 2. The IUT
   871	
   872	An IUT MUST:
   873	
   874	- Expose chapter 07's HTTP binding at a deployment-chosen base URL.
   875	- Accept an experiment configuration whose shape matches
   876	  `experiment-config.schema.json`.
   877	
   878	Anything else — language, deployment topology, persistence, auth
   879	scheme, scaling profile — is a deployment choice. Chapter 07 §11
   880	enumerates further latitude.
   881	
   882	## 3. Assertion vocabulary
   883	
   884	Every assertion in the v1 suite is keyed off a normative MUST in
   885	chapters 02 / 04 / 05 / 06 / 07 / 08. The suite does NOT assert
   886	SHOULDs; SHOULDs are interop guidance, not interop contracts.
   887	
   888	When the spec evolves, the suite evolves with it. A change that
   889	removes a MUST or downgrades it to SHOULD MUST be accompanied by a
   890	matching scenario removal or rewrite.
   891	
   892	The suite intentionally does NOT certify §1.3-class atomicity or §3.2
   893	unforgeability properties; black-box testing cannot prove the absence
   894	of a sufficiently-narrow window or the absence of a sufficiently-weak
   895	random source. The v1 suite asserts the testable consequences of these
   896	invariants (event presence, uniqueness across observed claims) and
   897	labels the regression-style tests as such.
   898	
   899	## 4. Conformance levels
   900	
   901	The v0 spec defines exactly one wire binding (chapter 07 HTTP). The
   902	suite drives every IUT through it; transport-neutral semantic tests
   903	vs. per-binding wire tests cannot be meaningfully separated until a
   904	second binding exists. Levels are therefore distinguished by
   905	**scenario coverage**, not transport:
   906	
   907	- **v1** — task-store and event-log MUSTs from chapters 02 / 04 /
   908	  05 / 07 plus the chapter-08 storage MUSTs the wire binding exposes
   909	  (§1.1, §1.7). v1 does NOT cover chapter-03 role contracts or the
   910	  chapter-06 integrator atomicity ladder.
   911	
   912	- **v1+roles** — adds chapter-03 role-contract scenarios (per-role
   913	  submission semantics, backpressure, idempotency). Lands in chunk
   914	  11c.
   915	
   916	- **v1+roles+integrator** — adds chapter-06 integrator scenarios
   917	  (squash shape, eval-manifest shape, `work/*` access discipline,
   918	  the §3.4 atomicity ladder under transport-indeterminate failures).
   919	  Lands in chunk 11d.
   920	
   921	A future spec lineage that introduces a second wire binding will at
   922	that point split the suite into transport-neutral semantic tests +
   923	per-binding wire tests, and chapter 09 will gain a `core` level
   924	claimable by IUTs implementing only the semantic layer. The marker
   925	structure in [`conformance/`](../../conformance/) anticipates that
   926	refactor but does not enable it in v0.
   927	
   928	## 5. Scenario index (v1; v1+roles and v1+roles+integrator extend)
   929	
   930	| Group | Scope | Spec citations |
   931	|---|---|---|
   932	| Task lifecycle | Every legal/illegal transition. | 04 §1, §3, §4 |
   933	| Claim tokens | Freshness, authorization, no-reclaim-while-claimed. | 04 §3 |
   934	| Submit idempotency | Content-equivalent / divergent / post-terminal. | 04 §4.2, §4.4 |
   935	| Reclamation | Case matrix; token invalidation; trial reconciliation. | 04 §5 |
   936	| Atomicity (regression test) | State + event consistency around a transition. Best-effort, not a certification. | 04 §1.3 |
   937	| Event envelope | Chapter-05 §1 envelope shape; uniqueness. | 05 §1, §1.1 |
   938	| Per-type event payloads | Each registered type's required fields. | 05 §3 |
   939	| Composite commits | Implement-dispatch, implement-terminal, evaluate-terminal cases, implement-reclaim-with-starting-trial. | 05 §2.2 |
   940	| Event delivery | Total order, replay from cursor 0, at-least-once, long-poll subscribe. | 05 §4; 07 §6.2 |
   941	| Status codes | Each operation's spec-pinned status. | 07 §§2-6 |
   942	| Problem+json envelope | Shape + content-type. | 07 §7 |
   943	| Error vocabulary closure | Closed `eden://error/<name>` set; observed exhaustively. | 07 §7 |
   944	| Experiment-id header disagreement | 400 experiment-id-mismatch. | 07 §1.3 |
   945	| Integrate idempotency | Same-value / different-value / preconditions. | 07 §5 |
   946	
   947	Chunk 11c adds the v1+roles entries (chapter 03 role contracts);
   948	chunk 11d adds the v1+roles+integrator entries (chapter 06 integrator
   949	flows). The exact scenario lists for those levels are out of scope
   950	for the v1 chapter-09 ship; they will be appended in their respective
   951	chunks.
   952	
   953	## 6. Adapter (informative)
   954	
   955	A v1 IUT does NOT need to ship a Python adapter. The reference suite's
   956	adapter shape — under
   957	[`conformance/harness/adapter.py`](../../conformance/harness/adapter.py)
   958	— is one convenience for IUTs that prefer to integrate with the
   959	reference Python harness; it is not a normative requirement. A non-
   960	Python implementor MAY:
   961	
   962	- Write a Python `IutAdapter` subclass that spawns their service.
   963	- Run the suite against an already-running IUT pointed at by an
   964	  environment variable, via a thin Python adapter that simply
   965	  returns an `IutHandle` to that URL.
   966	- Re-implement the suite in another language entirely, asserting the
   967	  same MUSTs.
   968	
   969	The contract between an IUT and a conformance harness is the chapter
   970	07 HTTP binding. Everything else is convenience.
   971	
   972	## 7. Reference posture
   973	
   974	The reference implementation in [`reference/`](../../reference/) is
   975	one demonstration of v0 conformance at the highest currently-shipped
   976	level (v1 at the time chapter 09 first lands; v1+roles after chunk
   977	11c; v1+roles+integrator after chunk 11d). CI gates the reference
   978	impl on every level the suite has shipped, via the `conformance` job.
   979	A reference-impl test failure that cannot be cited to a normative
   980	MUST is either a suite bug or a spec gap; the resolution is one of:
   981	amend the suite, amend the spec, fix the impl. The reference impl
   982	does NOT have authority to reinterpret the spec.
   983	```
   984	
   985	The chapter is intentionally informative on the adapter shape and on
   986	the v0-reference auth mechanism (chapter 07 §12). Codex review round 0
   987	finding #3 prescribed exactly this: the spec must not require third-
   988	party implementations to expose a Python-harness-friendly lifecycle
   989	shim or a bearer-token auth scheme.
   990	
   991	### H. CI wiring
   992	
   993	New `conformance` job in [`.github/workflows/ci.yml`](../../.github/workflows/ci.yml):
   994	
   995	```yaml
   996	  conformance:
   997	    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
   998	    steps:
   999	      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
  1000	      - uses: astral-sh/setup-uv@v3
  1001	      - name: Install workspace
  1002	        run: uv sync --all-packages
  1003	      - name: Run conformance suite
  1004	        run: uv run pytest -q conformance/
  1005	      - name: Verify directionality (no reference imports outside adapters)
  1006	        run: |
  1007	          set -euo pipefail
  1008	          if grep -RnE '^(from|import) (reference|eden_)' \
  1009	            conformance/harness conformance/scenarios; then
  1010	            echo "FAIL: conformance/harness or conformance/scenarios import reference packages."
  1011	            exit 1
  1012	          fi
  1013	      - name: Verify scenario citations
  1014	        run: uv run python conformance/tools/check_citations.py
  1015	```
  1016	
  1017	The directionality check makes the layering explicit: `conformance/harness/`
  1018	and `conformance/scenarios/` MUST NOT import `reference/` packages.
  1019	`conformance/adapters/reference/` is allowed to (that's the layer
  1020	where the reference impl is taught how to be a subject).
  1021	
  1022	The job is **not** added to the branch-protection required-checks set
  1023	in this chunk. After 2-3 clean runs on `main`, a follow-up commit can
  1024	bump it.
  1025	
  1026	### I. Spec ↔ harness traceability
  1027	
  1028	Every test in the suite carries a docstring whose first line cites a
  1029	specific spec section, in the format
  1030	`spec/v0/<chapter>.md §<sec> — <one-line summary>`. Example:
  1031	
  1032	```python
  1033	def test_wrong_token_rejected(wire_client, claimed_task):
  1034	    """spec/v0/04-task-protocol.md §3.3 — submit with wrong token MUST be rejected.
  1035	
  1036	    Verifies that the task store rejects a submit operation whose token
  1037	    differs from the one issued at claim time.
  1038	    """
  1039	```
  1040	
  1041	`conformance/tools/check_citations.py` (also in this chunk):
  1042	
  1043	1. Walks every test under `conformance/scenarios/`.
  1044	2. Extracts the first docstring line.
  1045	3. Parses out `spec/v0/<chapter>.md §<sec>`.
  1046	4. Asserts the cited section exists (using the existing
  1047	   [`scripts/spec-xref-check.py`](../../scripts/spec-xref-check.py)
  1048	   helper as a model).
  1049	5. Validates that every entry in the chapter 09 §5 scenario index has
  1050	   at least one citing test (drift between the chapter and the suite
  1051	   is a CI failure — codex review round 0 implicit risk).
  1052	6. Emits a coverage report: which spec sections have at least one
  1053	   citing test, and the union of cited sections.
  1054	
  1055	CI fails if (3) doesn't parse, (4) doesn't resolve, or (5) leaves an
  1056	index entry uncovered.
  1057	
  1058	### J. AGENTS.md update
  1059	
  1060	Add to the Commands table:
  1061	
  1062	| `uv run pytest -q conformance/` | Run the conformance suite against the reference impl. |
  1063	| `uv run pytest -q conformance/ --iut-adapter=<module:Cls>` | Run the conformance suite against a non-reference IUT. |
  1064	| `uv run python conformance/tools/check_citations.py` | Verify every conformance test's docstring cites a real spec section. |
  1065	
  1066	And under "Plan-writing pitfalls", a new entry:
  1067	
  1068	> **Conformance assertions are spec citations, not impl observations.**
  1069	> When adding a scenario, the docstring's first line MUST cite a
  1070	> normative MUST in `spec/v0/<chapter>.md §<sec>`; CI checks the
  1071	> citation resolves AND that the cited section is in the chapter 09
  1072	> §5 scenario index. If the assertion describes behavior the reference
  1073	> impl exhibits but no spec MUST mandates, the choice is to amend the
  1074	> spec (so the assertion is grounded) or drop the assertion (it's an
  1075	> impl-detail observation). Codifying impl observations as conformance
  1076	> assertions silently creates a second source of truth and locks
  1077	> third-party implementations into reference-impl quirks.
  1078	
  1079	### K. Self-host / packaging
  1080	
  1081	The harness is invoked **without** the conformance/ package being a
  1082	development dependency of the reference services — i.e. running
  1083	`uv run pytest -q reference/` doesn't pull in conformance machinery.
  1084	This is enforced by:
  1085	
  1086	- `conformance/pyproject.toml` declares `conformance` as a separate uv
  1087	  workspace member with its own dependency closure (pytest, httpx,
  1088	  aiohttp, pytest-ordering, pytest-json-report).
  1089	- The reference services' tests do NOT import from `conformance/`.
  1090	- Root `pyproject.toml` lists `conformance` under
  1091	  `[tool.uv.workspace] members` but reference packages don't depend
  1092	  on it.
  1093	
  1094	A non-Python implementor can clone the repo, run `uv sync --package
  1095	conformance` (or any equivalent venv), and point pytest at their
  1096	adapter. They never run `uv sync --all-packages`.
  1097	
  1098	## Test plan
  1099	
  1100	In addition to the scenarios themselves (which are the primary unit of
  1101	test for this chunk), three external verifications run before merge:
  1102	
  1103	1. **Reference adapter passes the v1 suite end to end.** `uv run pytest
  1104	   -q conformance/` exits 0. CI's new `conformance` job gates this.
  1105	
  1106	2. **Self-validation meta test passes.** All three sub-assertions
  1107	   (control passes, broken fails on the specific test ID, hit counter
  1108	   ≥ 1) succeed.
  1109	
  1110	3. **Citation check passes.** `uv run python conformance/tools/check_citations.py`
  1111	   exits 0. Specifically: every test cites a resolvable section AND
  1112	   every chapter-09 §5 scenario-index entry has at least one citing
  1113	   test.
  1114	
  1115	Ad-hoc tests during implementation should additionally include:
  1116	
  1117	- **Per-test isolation.** Run the suite with `pytest -p no:cacheprovider
  1118	  -x --tb=short` and verify no state leaks between scenarios (no
  1119	  shared `event_id` clashes, no shared experiment_id reuse).
  1120	- **Random `experiment_id` per test prevents cross-talk.** Two
  1121	  scenarios that create tasks with the same payload do not see each
  1122	  other's tasks (this falls out of fresh-uuid + per-scenario adapter
  1123	  start, but worth confirming explicitly).
  1124	- **Shutdown discipline.** Run the suite with subprocess monitoring
  1125	  (`ps -ef` before / after) to verify no leaked task-store-server
  1126	  processes after pytest exits.
