   570	codex review round 0 finding #9.)
   571	
   572	#### E.5 Atomicity (best-effort regression test) (`test_atomicity.py`)
   573	
   574	```python
   575	@pytest.mark.conformance
   576	def test_task_state_change_visible_only_after_event_appended():
   577	    """spec/v0/04-task-protocol.md §1.3 — every state change MUST be
   578	    accompanied by its event, atomically.
   579	
   580	    NOTE: This is a best-effort regression test, not a certification of
   581	    the §1.3 atomicity invariant. A black-box poll-and-compare cannot
   582	    rule out that the IUT briefly exposed a state without its event in
   583	    a window narrower than the harness can observe; a Jepsen-style
   584	    linearizability check is out of scope for v1.
   585	
   586	    The test drives one transition while concurrently long-poll-
   587	    subscribing to the event log. The assertion is: when the
   588	    long-poll yields the next event, an immediate `GET /tasks/{T}`
   589	    MUST show a state consistent with that event. A subsequent
   590	    follow-up read MUST NOT regress the state. Any window where the
   591	    poll observes a state that the subsequent event does not match
   592	    is a finding.
   593	    """
   594	```
   595	
   596	The wording in the docstring matches what codex review round 0
   597	finding #4 prescribed: "best-effort black-box regression test, not the
   598	conformance proof of atomicity." Chapter 09 §3 explicitly notes that
   599	no v1 scenario certifies §1.3; the v1 suite asserts the testable
   600	consequences.
